In C language, you can use the library "inttypes.h" along with the data type "int64_t" to perform division of 64-bit integers accurately. 

The "inttypes.h" library provides format specifiers and functions for handling integer types, including the 64-bit integer type. And the "int64_t" is a signed integer type with a width of exactly 64 bits.

Here's an example of how you can use the "inttypes.h" library with "int64_t" data type to perform division:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <inttypes.h>

int main() {
    int64_t numerator = 123456789012345;
    int64_t denominator = 9876543210;
    int64_t result = numerator / denominator;

    printf("Result: %" PRId64 "\n", result);

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, the "%" PRId64 " format specifier is used to print the 64-bit integer value accurately.

Remember to include the "inttypes.h" library and declare variables of type "int64_t" to perform division with precision and accuracy.

